caption: Ramen is a bit pricey but understandable considering where it's located. Nothing special about the place but you can't go wrong with the items they have on the menu.

First time having ramen from this place & I don’t want to seem rude nor picky. The ramen just wasn’t that good honestly. The noodles aren’t fresh and the egg was very old tasting. Couldn’t get past one bite , so I decided to put it to the side. Although the broth was good it wasn’t anything special. The shrimp and chicken and pork and everything which includes in the seafood ramen was good. The octopus balls yaki tori excuse my spelling if it is wrong was very good!!! Overall my ramen experience was not that good and maybe it was just my experience since the reviews seem to be great. This is strictly my experience and I’m not saying this is a bad place. I could of just came at a bad time.

There aren't too many Japanese style ramen restaurants in the area so when you're craving for a big bowl of ramen with some nicely charred pork and a perfectly cooked egg, this place can hit the spot. The broth used to be way too salty when they first opened up but they've since adjusted it and it's a lot better now. I prefer thinner noodles over thick and I always add all the extra spices offered at the bar or on the table in front of you. There are seats at the bar, facing the chef, or a few small tables at the back. You can hang your jackets on the wall hooks and there are plenty of outlets at the bar to charge your phone. There's usually only 2 or 3 people working there but the wait for the food isn't terribly long and everyone is very friendly.
Excellent quality noodles and broth. Highly recommend getting thin noodles and extra garlic paste.

Very interesting small spot, with tables for 2-4 and bar seating. The ramen was decent, very simple ingredients, though they only have chicken or vegetable broth. Good if you're looking for vegetarian options or are a picky eater. Meat wise they have pork or chicken options. Two types of noodles and lots of veggies to choose from. They have some apetizers as well, we got the veggie dumplings (which were okay) and takoyaki (which was surprisingly decent). Portions are good to share and one bowl of ramen is super filling.
It was okay, I was expecting more from it. The staten Island mall has better Ramen actually.

Overall it's good for the price and amount - you don't have many options in this part of town so I can see how locals could say this is the best they've ever had. I guess they've never tried Ippudo.

You wouldn't normally find a authentic ramen shop in Bensonhurst so it's great to see one in the neighborhood especially a few feet from the N subway train stop. Very convenient. The interior is nicely decorated and there is a long ramen bar for seating with just 2 tables in the back. The shop is definitely for a quick meal for small groups or solo. Very Japanese style. The pork buns were a bit fatty and too much of the mayo sauce overpowered everything to a fatty level. The ramen though was great. Decent pork, nice tendery chewy ramen but the standout was the broth. The broth was flavorful and balanced. I usually don't drink a whole bowl of broth as it is too salty but this one i finished it all for a hot winter night.
Food was good.  Good flavors, could use additional appetizer options like those tapas in st. Marks place in manhattan.

CASH ONLY.  Not the best ramen in NYC, but good enough as a local neighborhood ramen joint. Nice to have another option other than Chinese Food or pizza in the neighborhood.  The waitstaff here are very attentive, granted albeit inexperience. They offer the dessert menu as soon as we finish ordering appetizers and ramen, was a bit strange since I don't know how full I will be after finishing my soon to be dinner. They constantly refilled my tea cup, probably 5 times, which I'm not complaining since I drink a lot of liquids.  Ordered edamame, char sui buns, bonito ramen, shoyu ramen, and rain cake. For the ramen there is an option for either thick or thin noodles. The bonito ramen is a fish and chicken stock, and it was not as thick or heavy soup base as the typical pork broth use in many NYC ramen joints. It's was seasoned well but it was a bit lacking in the fish flavor. The egg in the ramen was a delight. The char Sui bun and pork slices were season wonderful. Though the char sui bun can be missed, just pork slices, lettuce and mayo sauce. The dessert was a delightful cooling and refreshing dessert. The "rain cake" is a flavorless jello but it comes with syrup that provided just enough sweetness.  There is bar seating like traditional ramen joints, and a few table seating in the back.

This is probably one of the worse ramen places in NYC but it is on the lower end of price spectrum so I guess you get what you pay for. The bar seats have outlets to charge whatever devices. I ordered an R1 which is the Umai Pitan Ramen. The char siu is not bad but not as tender and flavorful as other ramen joints. The broth, on the other hand, tasted gross and a little fishy and the noodles were nothing to write home about. The best part of the ramen was the spicy powder I dumped into the bowl.
